<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="525" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,150,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,870,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Newly examined material enables supplementation of available descriptions of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Curtis, J." pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="441 - 476" refId="ref8290" refString="Curtis, J. (1845) Descriptions, &amp; c. of the insects collected by Captain P. P. King in the survey of the Straits of Magellan. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, 19, 441 - 476. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1842. tb 00371. x" type="journal article" year="1845">Curtis 1845</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Solier, A. J." box="[221,352,906,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="5 - 285" refId="ref10194" refString="Solier, A. J. (1851) Insectos. Coleopteros. In: Historia fisica y politica de Chile segun documentos adquiridos en esta republica durante doce anos de residencia en ella y publicada bajo los auspicios del supremo gobierno por Claudio Gay. Zoologia. Tomo Quinto. Museo de Historia Natural de Santiago, Paris, pp. 5 - 285." type="book chapter" year="1851">Solier 1851</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mulsant, E. &amp; Rey, C." box="[364,620,906,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="65 - 157" refId="ref9986" refString="Mulsant, E. &amp; Rey, C. (1859) Essai d'une division des derniers Melasomes. Opuscules Entomologiques, 9, 65 - 157. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 2682" type="journal article" year="1859">Mulsant and Rey 1859</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Aballay, F. H. &amp; Flores, G. E. &amp; Silvestro, V. A. &amp; Zanetti, N. I. &amp; Centeno, N. D." box="[629,844,907,934]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="703 - 726" refId="ref7819" refString="Aballay, F. H., Flores, G. E., Silvestro, V. A., Zanetti, N. I. &amp; Centeno, N. D. (2016) An illustrated key to, and diagnoses of the species of Tenebrionidae (Coleoptera) associated with decaying carcasses in Argentina. Annales Zoologici, 66, 703 - 726. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 00034541 ANZ 2016.66.4.021" type="journal article" year="2016">
Aballay 
<emphasis box="[724,773,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
) with data on male and female terminalia. Therefore, a redescription is provided below and a new diagnosis is provided to accommodate this species with its new congeners.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,150,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">
The following features place this species within 
<taxonomicName box="[765,855,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Lodinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[765,855,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Lodinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marcuzzi, G." box="[873,1050,1014,1041]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref9624" refString="Marcuzzi, G. (1954) Studies on the fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands: no. 22. Tenebrionid beetles of Curacao, Aruba, Bonaire, and the Venezuelan Islands. Natuurwetenschappelijke Studiekring voor Suriname, 10, 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1954">Marcuzzi 1954</bibRefCitation>
, 1982): median lobe of aedeagus widely projecting between parameres; parameres with truncate apex (
<figureCitation box="[929,995,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1675,1699]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,525,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-169@3.[151,1436,525,1651]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogeny of subtribe Blapstinina. Figured topology was recovered in maximum likelihood analysis using IQ- Tree. Ultrafast bootstrap values (1,000 replicates) (integers) and posterior probabilities (20 million generations) acquired in Bayesian analysis (decimals) are displayed in red. The three investigated Blapstinina species are displayed in blue. Male genitalia (1–4) of selected species (dorsal views) are illustrated on the left. Topologies of collapsed clades (‘remaining Opatrini’ &amp; ‘Dendarini + Pedininini + Playtonotini’) are fully consistent with those presented in Lumen et al. (2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964431" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964431/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,150,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[199,429,1086,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Lodinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctulatus">
<emphasis box="[199,429,1086,1112]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Lodinus punctulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from its congeners by differing pronotal structure (
<bibRefCitation author="Marcuzzi, G." pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref9624" refString="Marcuzzi, G. (1954) Studies on the fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands: no. 22. Tenebrionid beetles of Curacao, Aruba, Bonaire, and the Venezuelan Islands. Natuurwetenschappelijke Studiekring voor Suriname, 10, 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1954">Marcuzzi 1954</bibRefCitation>
): anterior angles rounded, not prominent (pointed and prominent in remaining species); punctures sparsely distributed on disc (&gt;1.0 diameters apart vs. &lt;
<quantity box="[675,755,1157,1184]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.905" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" unit="in" value="0.75">0.75 in</quantity>
remaining species). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[1147,1309,1157,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Lodinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctulatus">
<emphasis box="[1147,1309,1157,1183]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">L. punctulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species within the genus which possesses subparallel parameres in their apical portion (slightly narrowing towards apex in 
<emphasis box="[241,448,1228,1254]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[241,419,1228,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Austrocaribius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venezuelensis">L. venezuelensis</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
Figs 46 and 
<quantity box="[587,645,1228,1254]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1684" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" unit="in" value="46.0">46 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Marcuzzi, G." box="[652,824,1228,1254]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" pagination="239 - 269" refId="ref9671" refString="Marcuzzi, G. (1983) Description of the external male genitalia of some neotropical tenebrionidae coleoptera heteromera. Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 44 (2), 239 - 269." type="journal article" year="1983">Marcuzzi 1983</bibRefCitation>
; strongly indented in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[1069,1192,1229,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Lodinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araguae">
<emphasis box="[1069,1192,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">L. araguae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
— 
<figureCitation box="[1223,1310,1228,1254]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[170,1399,602,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-194@9.[151,1436,597,1836]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Morphology of female and male terminalia of selected Blapstinina species. (A–C) Lodinus punctulatus comb. nov., (D) Lodinus araguae comb. nov., (E, F) Blapstinus tibialis. (A, B, E) ovipositor, (C, F) genital tubes, (D) parameres. Abbreviations: ag—accessory gland, b—hooked baculus of c4, c1–c4—subsequent lobes of coxites, g—gonostylus, sp—sper- matheca, vag—vagina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964437/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
). Lastly, as of this redescription, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Kamiński &amp; Lumen &amp; Kanda &amp; Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[389,550,1263,1289]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Lodinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctulatus">
<emphasis box="[389,550,1263,1289]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">L. punctulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species of the genus known from south of the equator (
<figureCitation box="[1295,1364,1263,1290]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[205,1382,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[205,1382,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution of Lodinus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964439/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="525" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,150,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,1299,1325]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Redescription</emphasis>
. Length 
<quantity box="[463,599,1299,1325]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.55" metricValueMax="6.2" metricValueMin="4.9" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" unit="mm" value="5.55" valueMax="6.2" valueMin="4.9">4.9–6.2 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[679,816,1299,1325]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="525" unit="mm" value="2.35" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.6 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[825,887,1299,1325]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Body</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[902,992,1299,1325]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1498,1522]" captionTargetBox="[163,1434,203,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-27@7.[151,1436,200,1474]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphology of studied Blapstinina species. Habitus photographs and diagnostic features. (A–C) Lodinus punctulatus comb. nov., (D–F) Lodinus araguae comb. nov., (G) Blapstinus tibialis, (H, I) Blapstinus grandis. (B) protarsus, (C) mesotarsus, (D) last 5 antennomeres, (I) apical tip of epipleura." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964433" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964433/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
): dull brown to black; dorsal and ventral surfaces matte; ovate-oblong; widest at 2/3 of elytral length; weakly convex in lateral view; evenly covered with fine setae dorsally. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[366,439,1370,1396]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Head:</emphasis>
Epistoma broadly convex; punctures equal to diameter of an ommatidium (distributed 1– 2 diameters apart); setae equal in length to intervals between punctures. Fronto-epistomal suture slightly marked on sides. Epistoma weakly emarginate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[564,695,1441,1467]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Prothorax:</emphasis>
Pronotum narrowing anteriorly, apical angles sharp. Lateral margin slightly rounded; marginated. Basal width slightly narrower than humeri; basal margin slightly bisinuate. Disc sparsely but noticeably covered with setae; finely punctate (punctures 1–3 diameters apart). Lateral sides marginated. Hypomeron dull and rugose; hypomeron impressed on sides. Intercoxal process of prosternum not depressed in lateral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[321,514,1582,1608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Scutellar shield:</emphasis>
Pentagonal, of equal width and length, finely punctate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1133,1287,1583,1609]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Pterothorax:</emphasis>
Elytral striae shallow and punctate (1–2 diameters apart). Striae not joining prior humeral angle. Intervals flat, punctate (0.5–1.0 diameters apart), with noticeable microsculpture. Epipleura finely punctate. Metathoracic wings well developed. Metaventrite long, sparsely punctate; sparse setae present. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[826,892,1689,1715]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Legs:</emphasis>
Protibia apically dilated with lateral projection at apex. Meso and meta tibia straight and dilated apically. Pro- and mesotarsomeres 2 and 3 dilated in males (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1498,1522]" captionTargetBox="[163,1434,203,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-27@7.[151,1436,200,1474]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphology of studied Blapstinina species. Habitus photographs and diagnostic features. (A–C) Lodinus punctulatus comb. nov., (D–F) Lodinus araguae comb. nov., (G) Blapstinus tibialis, (H, I) Blapstinus grandis. (B) protarsus, (C) mesotarsus, (D) last 5 antennomeres, (I) apical tip of epipleura." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964433" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964433/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 2B, C</figureCitation>
). Abdominal ventrites: Finely punctate, scattered with setae; intercoxal process narrowly rounded; ventrite 5 with posterior margin evenly rounded, not bordered. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[776,891,1795,1821]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[908,975,1795,1822]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1675,1699]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,525,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-169@3.[151,1436,525,1651]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogeny of subtribe Blapstinina. Figured topology was recovered in maximum likelihood analysis using IQ- Tree. Ultrafast bootstrap values (1,000 replicates) (integers) and posterior probabilities (20 million generations) acquired in Bayesian analysis (decimals) are displayed in red. The three investigated Blapstinina species are displayed in blue. Male genitalia (1–4) of selected species (dorsal views) are illustrated on the left. Topologies of collapsed clades (‘remaining Opatrini’ &amp; ‘Dendarini + Pedininini + Playtonotini’) are fully consistent with those presented in Lumen et al. (2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964431" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964431/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
): whole tegmen evenly curved in lateral view. Apical part of aedeagus truncate; median lobe opening circular. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[938,1156,1831,1857]" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Female terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1172,1297,1831,1857]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[170,1399,602,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-194@9.[151,1436,597,1836]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Morphology of female and male terminalia of selected Blapstinina species. (A–C) Lodinus punctulatus comb. nov., (D) Lodinus araguae comb. nov., (E, F) Blapstinus tibialis. (A, B, E) ovipositor, (C, F) genital tubes, (D) parameres. Abbreviations: ag—accessory gland, b—hooked baculus of c4, c1–c4—subsequent lobes of coxites, g—gonostylus, sp—sper- matheca, vag—vagina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5964437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5964437/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="525">Fig. 3A–C</figureCitation>
): Ovipositor with paraprocts slightly longer than coxites. Paraproct does not shield valvifer and other lobes (directed basally). Valvifer wide and short; second lobe elongate; third one semicircular (about 0.5 of height of third one); apical lobe rounded, situated apically, sclerotised at outer and inner edges, inner sclerotisation hook-like, gonostyli on dorsal side, directed inwards. Proctiger covering nearly whole ovipositor. Vagina without sclerites. Spermatheca with narrow duct. Spiculum ventrale short.
</paragraph>
